comments.body: Thank you, @mikecardwell! Being more of an orni guy I know next to nothing about (non-avian) reptiles, so I had no idea how uncommon these traits were, in fact I didn't even know what to look for to tell apart C. scutulatus from C. atrox until I tried to identify all of my observations just before upolading them! This one was the only one I was certain to be a C. scutulatus on first instance. I can e-mail you the HD pohots if you're interesed.

Hi @eliphaleth, you've documented a couple very interesting but uncommon traits of C. scutulatus in this observation. Most interesting is the defensive lateral neck flattening. This has been described in the literature before but is only rarely observed, so far as I know. The other is the aberrant dorsal pattern where so many of the dorsal rhombs are merged, especially on the neck where the dorsal "diamonds" disappear and look more like stripes. Finally, some great photos...in focus with the facial markings and crown scales easily visible. Nice job!!
